// Reject fixture: out_of_scope_type_param_actor_method — a type-parameter name
// is in scope only for the item that declares it. `id` declares `<T>`, so `T`
// is valid inside `id`. The actor method `bad` declares no type params, so its
// `x: T` names a type that is out of scope. The checker must report it at the
// annotation with `unknown type `T``, rather than exempt it merely because `id`
// declares a `T` somewhere program-wide and leak an opaque `Ty::named("T")`
// that only surfaces downstream as `E_MIR: unknown type` at the MIR boundary.
//
// Companion to out_of_scope_type_param (free fn): proves the scope-aware
// exemption holds on the actor-method signature path, not just free functions.
//
// Harness verb: hew check
// Expected: rejected with `unknown type `T`` at `bad`'s parameter annotation.
fn id<T>(x: T) -> T { x }

actor Worker {
    fn bad(x: T) -> i64 { 0 }
    receive fn run() {}
}

fn main() -> i64 { 0 }
